 to be dying in the 1860s, but which was given new strength from the 1880s. It delivers a riposte to portrayals of the lower clergy as a marginalised group that was driven to defend itself from liberal attacks by turning to anti-liberal, antisemitic action, as well as exposing the nurturing role played by senior clergy. As the book reveals, the Church in Vienna as a whole was determined to counter liberalism, to the point of welcoming any authoritarian regime that would do so.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAntisemitismzAustriazViennaxHistoryy19th century. 0aAntisemitismzAustriazViennaxHistoryy20th century. 0aChristianity and antisemitismzAustriazViennaxHistoryy19th century. 0aChristianity and antisemitismzAustriazViennaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh  aAntisemitism.  aAustria.  aAuthoritarianism.  aChurch.  aEurope.  aHabsburg.  aLiberalism.  aModernism.  aNationalism.  aVienna.1 aCarter-Sinclair, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614487440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526144874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526144874/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles